textAnnotations.description:
HYMNS.
4 And I have brought to thee,
Down from my home above,
Salvation full and free,
My pardon and My love;
I bring, I bring rich gifts to thee,
What hast thou brought to me?
No. 189.
1 Grace! 'tis a charming sound,
Harmonious to the ear:
Heaven with the echo shall re-
sound,
And all the earth shall hear.
2 Grace first contrived the way
To save rebellious man;
And all the steps that grace dis-
play
Which drew the wondrous plan.
3 Grace led my roving feet
To tread the heavenly road;
And new supplies each hour I
meet,
While pressing on to God.
4 Grace all the work shall crown,
Through everlasting days;
It lays in heaven the topmost
stone,
And well deserves the praise.
No. 190.
1 Work, for the night is coming,
Work through the morning
hours;
Work, while the dew is sparkling,
Work 'mid springing flowers;
Work, when the day grows
brighter,
Work in the glowing sun;
Work, for the night is coming,
When man's work is done.
2 Work, for the night is coming,
Work through the sunny noon;
Fill brightest hours with labor,
Rest comes sure and soon.
Give every flying minute
Something to keep in store;
Work, for the night is coming,
When man works no more.
3 Work, for the night is coming,
Under the sunset skies;
While their bright tints are glow-
ing,
Work, for the daylight flies.
Work, till the last beam fadeth,
Fadeth to shine no more;
Work, while the night is darken-
ing,
When man's work is o'er.
No. 191.
1 Thou dear Redeemer,dying Lamb,
I love to hear of Thee;
No music's like Thy charming
name,
Nor half so sweet can be. .
2 O, let me ever hear Thy voice,
In mercy to me speak;
In Thee, my Priest, will I rejoice,
Thou great Melchisedec !
3 My Jesus, shall be still my theme,
While in the world I stay;
I'll sing my Jesus' lovely name,
When all things else decay.
4 When I appear in yonder cloud,
With all the favored throng,
Then will I sing more sweet,
more loud,
And Christ shall be my song.
JOHN CENNICK, 1745, a.
No. 192.
C. M.
1 God moves in a mysterious way,
His wonders to perform:
160
He plants His footsteps in the sea,
And rides upon the storm.
2 Ye fearful saints, fresh courage
take ;
The clouds ye so much dread
Are big with mercy, and shall
break
With blessing on your head.
3
